# üìù How to Rename a File in a GitHub Repository

This guide explains how to rename a file (including subfiles or nested files) in a GitHub repository using both the web interface and the command line.

---

## üîπ Option 1: Rename via GitHub Web Interface

### Steps:
1. Navigate to the repository on GitHub.
2. Browse to the file you want to rename.
3. Click the file name to open it.
4. In the top-right corner, click the **pencil icon** (Edit this file).
5. In the filename field at the top, change the name of the file.
6. Optionally, update the file contents.
7. Scroll down and enter a **commit message**.
8. Choose whether to commit directly to the branch or create a new branch.
9. Click **Commit changes**.

> ‚ö†Ô∏è Note: You must have write access to the repository to rename files directly.

---

## üîπ Option 2: Rename Using Git Locally

### Prerequisites:
- Git installed
- Access to the repository (via HTTPS or SSH)
- Proper permissions

### Steps:
```bash
# Clone the repository (if not already cloned)
git clone https://github.com/your-org/your-repo.git
cd your-repo

# Rename the file
git mv path/to/old-filename.ext path/to/new-filename.ext

# Stage and commit the change
git commit -m "Renamed file from old-filename.ext to new-filename.ext"

# Push the change to GitHub
git push origin main  # or your working branch
